05794nam a22007935i 9789633864500DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022hu     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1338838502  a97896338645007 a10.1515/97896338645002doi  a(DE-B1597)633596  a(OCoLC)1336891951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aDX301b.M57 2022 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.8914/9708223/eng/202207201 aMirga-Kruszelnicka, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMobilizing Romani Ethnicity :bRomani Political Activism in Argentina, Colombia and Spain /cAnna Mirga-Kruszelnicka. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Romani Studies Book Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction. Personal equation: Where did it all start? -- tChapter 1 Defining Ethnic Mobilization—A Synergic Approach -- tChapter 2 Political Opportunities—Understanding the Broader Context -- tChapter 3 Romani Ethnic Mobilization in a Comparative Perspective. Looking into the Case-Study Countries -- tChapter 4 Who Is Doing the Mobilizing? Anatomy of Romani Ethnic Mobilization Through the Prism of the Actors -- tChapter 5 Mobilizing Frames? Identity and Interests Intertwined -- tChapter 6 Mobilizing Romani Ethnicity for Collective Action -- tConclusions Mobilizing for Change? Limits and Potential of Romani Ethnic Mobilization -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Roma issue is generally treated as a European matter. Indeed, the Roma are the largest European minority—their presence outside of Europe is a result of various waves of migration over the past four hundred years. Likewise, the stereotypes associated with the Roma—the problematized, stigmatized status of a “Gypsy” as well as the historical and contemporary manifestations of antigypsyism—are also of European origin. This book claims, however, that the perception of Roma being strictly a European issue is flawed, and that re-connecting the Roma issue globally represents an important learning experience and an added value. The book offers a critical exploration of Romani political activism in Colombia and Argentina, and compares it to that in Spain, narrated from the intimate perspective of Romani actors themselves. By outlining parallel lineages of Romani activism in three countries and on two continents, the author arrives at broad conclusions regarding the nature of ethnic mobilization. Mirga-Kruszelnicka proposes a new synergetic conceptualization of this multidirectional concept as an interplay between political opportunities, mobilizing structures, and frames of identity. Contributing to the vivid debate about the relationship between the researcher and the researched, the book also includes an original discussion of the positionality of scholars of Romani background.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical participationzArgentina. 0aPolitical participationzChile. 0aPolitical participationzSpain. 0aRomaniesxPolitical activityzArgentina. 0aRomaniesxPolitical activityzChile. 0aRomaniesxPolitical activityzSpain. 0aRomanieszArgentinaxEthnic identity. 0aRomanieszChilexEthnic identity. 0aRomanieszSpainxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aRoma.  acomparative studies.  aethnic minorities.  aethnic mobilization.  apolitical activism.1 aBrooks, Ethel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European 